<br>
Thank you for getting me thinking about something. The Spurned, aka all casters save necros, can worship Innoruuk, but may not. Necros MUST.<br>
<br>
The 1st light site that has alot of info., talks about how the Shissar(Sp?) taught magery to the Teir'dal. They were the first casters among thier ilk.<br>
<br>
Now the current King and Queen are ones who took up the name Thex, but are not of that blood. Some say the Queen was taught necromancy by Innoruuk, hence the must worship thing. Innoruuk is the source of necromatic power for the Teir'dal. <br>
<br>
Now supposedly the spurned are called that because after necromancy arose they were cast down from the place of primary power.The necros made a power bid and won basically.<br>
<br>
If you note the asian flavor of the lodge of the dead this holds yet another rumor, that the art of necromancy was put into the culture by Dragons.<br>
<br>
You should read the history of Mayong Mistmoor on the site, its good.<br>
<br>
I don't think Innoruuk created dark elves in the proper use of the word. When you create one its says their race REGARDS him as the father. I think the Teir'dals corruption was  an evolution, from magery to necromancy and Innoruuk.<br>
<br>
Perhaps Innoruuk was the first God of the elven people, but when they came up from the earth they were seduced by the surface world and Tunare. Maybe this angered Innoruuk and produced the warring cultures you see today. Some that stayed with Him, and the ones that left.<br>
<br>
I know the history says he tortured the first elven king and queen twisting them to his image etc. I think however that is a metaphor that speaks to what the art and worship has done to the people over time.<br>
<br>
I know this is off to a degree and certainly incomplete, but I think I am on to something. I know my character in game believes this, that the creation story is a myth and metaphorical.<br>
<br>
Anyway thats something to think about., heck I never knew what all those rays coming out of snake heads meant in 3rd gate and on the doors of najena for example. Its the Shissar, the masters of magic who taught the dark elves magery.<br>
<br>
Outside of the game we must attribute meaning to life and decide what to believe and whatnot. I think its a good idea for Teir'dal , for example, to develope contrasting ideas on framework of the game history.<br>
